[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Generated by Rashida M Private Discover Your Next Favorite Book: Top 10 Reads for Every Personality Type Generated with sparks and insights from 12 sources Have you ever wondered why certain books captivate you completely while others leave you struggling to finish the first chapter? The answer lies deeper than simple taste preferences—it's woven into the very fabric of your personality. Just as our fingerprints are unique, our reading preferences are shaped by our psychological makeup, cognitive patterns, and the mental frameworks that define how we process the world around us. The connection between personality and reading preference isn't just intuitive speculation—it's backed by compelling research. According to 16Personalities1, 83% of all research respondents say they consider reading an important part of their lives, but the types of books that resonate most deeply vary dramatically based on personality traits. With over 6.2 million votes cast in the 2024 Goodreads Choice Awards (Goodreads2), we can observe clear patterns emerging in what different personality types gravitate toward. Whether you're a methodical planner who finds satisfaction in systematic world-building or a free spirit drawn to mystical poetry and unconventional narratives, understanding your personality type can unlock a treasure trove of books perfectly aligned with your psychological preferences. This comprehensive guide will explore the most compelling reads for every major personality type, featuring both timeless classics that have stood the test of time and the hottest releases capturing readers' imaginations in 2024. The Science Behind Personality-Driven Reading Preferences Before diving into specific recommendations, it's essential to understand the psychological mechanisms that drive our reading choices. Research from 16Personalities1 reveals fascinating patterns in how different cognitive functions create distinct reading behaviors and preferences. The Four Fundamental Reading Archetypes The data shows clear correlations between personality traits and reading habits: Introverted vs. Extraverted Reading Patterns: Introverted types are more likely to prefer science fiction/fantasy than their Extraverted counterparts (16Personalities1) Introverts often use books as gateways to explore complex inner worlds and escape into richly detailed universes Extraverted types frequently gravitate toward character-driven narratives that mirror their focus on human connections and social dynamics Intuitive vs. Observant Preferences: Intuitive types show stronger preference for science fiction/fantasy compared to Observant types Observant types prefer realistic, technical/educational books and mystery/thrillers more than Intuitive types do (16Personalities1) Intuitive personalities seek books that challenge conventional thinking and explore abstract concepts Sensing types prefer practical narratives with clear, actionable insights they can apply to their lives Reading Engagement by Personality Role The research reveals striking differences in how much different personality types value reading: Diplomats (NF types): 85% consider reading important Analysts (NT types): 84% find reading significant Sentinels (SJ types): 74% value reading Explorers (SP types): 66% prioritize reading (16Personalities1) This data suggests that while some personality types naturally gravitate toward reading more than others, when they do engage with books, they have remarkably distinct preferences that align with their fundamental cognitive functions. Genre Preferences Across Personality Types The most popular genre across all personality types is science fiction and fantasy, with 47% of survey respondents preferring this genre (16Personalities1). However, significant variations exist: Mediators (INFPs) and Logicians (INTPs) are virtually tied as the two types with the greatest affinity for books about distant, imaginary places and fantastic realities Executives (ESTJs) and Consuls (ESFJs) are the least likely to select fantasy/science fiction as their chosen genre Executives are the only personality type to choose technical/educational material as their favorite genre Consuls are the only personality type to choose mystery/thrillers as their favorite genre (16Personalities1) Interestingly, poetry is the least-read style of literature, with only 3% of respondents saying they enjoy reading verse the most (16Personalities1). 1. The Analytical Architects: Strategic Thinkers (INTJ, INTP) Understanding the Analytical Mind Analytical Architects represent the most intellectually demanding readers in the personality spectrum. These individuals thrive on complexity, systematic analysis, and books that reward careful, methodical thinking. Architects (INTJs) find moral ambiguity and the complexity of human behavior almost clinically interesting, while Logicians (INTPs) are always looking for a different angle and appreciate anything that challenges conventional thinking (16Personalities1). INTJ Reading Preferences and Recommendations Core Reading Philosophy: INTJs prefer books with simple characters and complex plots that explore moral ambiguity (16Personalities1). They're drawn to systematic analysis of power structures and grand-scale narratives. For Enjoyment: Frankenstein (also called The Modern Prometheus) by Mary Shelley - sometimes called the first science fiction novel and an example of early feminist writing (16Personalities1) For Growth: Flowers for Algernon by Daniel Keyes - recommended to watch for the roles of intellect and emotion and the way they manifest at different points in Charlie's life (16Personalities1) 2024 Trending Picks for INTJs: According to Charlotte Dune's 2024 Holiday MBTI Book Gift Guide3, current INTJ favorites include: The Art of War by Sun Tzu The Conquest of Gaul by Jane P. Gardner (Editor) and S. A. Handford (Translator) Player of Games by Iain Banks (from The Culture Series) Quantum Psychology: How Brain Software Programs You and Your World by Robert Anton Wilson Thinking in Systems by Donella H. Meadows Alternative Recommendations: Seveneves by Neal Stephenson - INTJs will love the grand, complex scale of Seveneves. This story is filled with depth and a big-picture, futuristic vision that will captivate the INTJ mind (Psychology Junkie4) INTP Reading Preferences and Recommendations Core Reading Philosophy: INTPs consume books that have twists and a variety of themes throughout. They typically appreciate fantasy/science fiction more than other personality types do, but anything that challenges conventional thinking is likely to attract their attention (16Personalities1). For Enjoyment: Fight Club by Chuck Palahniuk - a book with many twists and many interpretations (16Personalities1) For Growth: Party of One: The Loners' Manifesto by Anneli Rufus (16Personalities1) 2024 Trending Picks for INTPs: From Charlotte Dune's guide3: Dune by Frank Herbert Scum Villain's Self-Saving System by Mo Xiang Tong Xiu Generations by William Strauss The Idiots by Dostoevsky Man and His Symbols by Carl Jung Extended INTP Preferences: According to Charlotte Dune3, INTPs sometimes don't read much, but others read extensively. Many like twisting and intricate portal fiction, LitRPG, deep snark, edgy content, classics, and hyper-intellectual works. They also enjoy manga and graphic novels with unique plots, elegant art books, and anything complex with layers. They have a particular affinity for world fiction, especially Russian, Japanese, and Chinese books. Alternative Recommendation: The Spy Who Came In From the Cold by John le Carré - This isn't a \"flashy\" spy story like James Bond or Jason Bourne, but its accuracy, honesty, and suspenseful pace will be spellbinding to INTPs (Psychology Junkie4) Why These Books Work for Analytical Architects Analytical Architects gravitate toward books that respect their intelligence and present genuinely challenging concepts. They appreciate authors who construct intricate puzzles that reward careful analysis and deep thinking. INTJs are particularly drawn to all logic with no romance novels, preferring something Elon Musk would read - sci-fi or dystopian classics for novels, and anything about power or complex systems for non-fiction (Charlotte Dune3). 2. The Empathetic Idealists: Value-Driven Readers (INFJ, INFP) Understanding the Idealist Mind Empathetic Idealists represent the most emotionally attuned and value-driven readers. These personalities seek books that explore the human condition, moral complexity, and the possibility of creating a better world. They're natural meaning-makers who want literature to validate their sense that life should have deeper purpose and significance. INFJ Reading Preferences and Recommendations Core Reading Philosophy: Advocates (INFJs) value equality and fairness as their standards. When they read fiction, they will probably appreciate books that contain strong moral overtones and endings that give a nod to justice served or that recognize justice denied (16Personalities1). For Enjoyment: The Joy Luck Club by Amy Tan - about the American dream, intergenerational cultural differences, and the often difficult relationships between mothers and their daughters (16Personalities1) For Growth: The Power of Unreasonable People: How Social Entrepreneurs Create Markets That Change the World by John Elkington and Pamela Hartigan (16Personalities1) 2024 Trending Picks for INFJs: Charlotte Dune's research3 reveals current INFJ favorites: Cultish by Amanda Montell Yellowface by R.F. Kuang Testosterone: The Story of the Hormone that Dominates and Divides Us by Carole Hooven Writing the Shadow: Turn Your Inner Darkness Into Words by Joanna Penn Suing for Silence: Sexual Violence and Defamation Law by Mandi Gray Curse and Cure: Magic for Real Life by Sabrina Scott True Friends: A Revolutionary Approach to Cultivating Conscious Feminine Friendships by Rochanda Ferelli Alternative Recommendation: The Divine Comedy by Dante Alighieri - INFJs will be mesmerized by Alighieri's visions of the afterlife; Inferno, Purgatorio, and Paradiso. In the poems and stories, readers will find inspiration, terror, adventure, monsters, and lessons of good and evil (Psychology Junkie4) Notable INFJ Insight: According to Charlotte Dune3, INFJs are most likely to be cult leaders, and thus like to read about cult leaders. They also enjoy non-fiction books related to health, spirituality, utopia, and ideal lives/self-optimization. INFP Reading Preferences and Recommendations Core Reading Philosophy: As Introverted as Mediators (INFPs) are, human connection is huge for them. These soft-hearted souls are moved by the plight of others. Often, their sense of purpose involves helping others live fuller lives (16Personalities1). For Enjoyment: The House on Mango Street by Sandra Cisneros - a series of vignettes that take place over a year in the life of a young Mexican American girl in Chicago (16Personalities1) For Growth: Between the World and Me by Ta-Nehisi Coates - a nonfiction book written in the form of a letter to Coates's son about the challenges of being Black in America (16Personalities1) 2024 Trending Picks for INFPs: From Charlotte Dune's guide3, INFPs are so mystical and gravitate toward: H.R. Giger Tarot by Giger and Akron Anything by Anais Nin The Magus by John Fowles Big Magic by Elizabeth Gilbert Eastern Mind Western Body by Anodea Judith Alternative Recommendation: The Lord of the Rings Book Series by J.R.R. Tolkien - INFPs will enjoy the fantastical, lush world of Middle Earth and the integrity and will-power of Frodo Baggins and his friends (Psychology Junkie4) Extended INFP Preferences: Anything about magic, eastern medicine, tarot, art, or poetics can work. Manga and graphic novels also appeal to INFPs (Charlotte Dune3). Why These Books Work for Empathetic Idealists Empathetic Idealists are drawn to stories that validate their deep belief in human potential and transformation. They seek books that explore moral complexity without losing hope, and narratives that show how individuals can make meaningful differences in the world. These personalities particularly appreciate works that blend the mystical with the practical, offering both spiritual insight and actionable wisdom for personal growth. 3. The Dynamic Leaders: Influence-Focused Readers (ENTJ, ENFJ) Understanding the Leadership Mind Dynamic Leaders approach reading as a tool for becoming more effective leaders and inspirers of others. They seek practical wisdom they can immediately apply to their leadership challenges, along with stories that illuminate the complexities of human motivation and organizational dynamics. ENTJ Reading Preferences and Recommendations Core Reading Philosophy: Due to their strategic and often ambitious actions, Commanders (ENTJs) often float to the top and into leadership positions. Even if they aren't leaders, their mindset is generally that of someone in charge (16Personalities1). Commanders are the type that's most likely to approach reading with a clear purpose in mind (16Personalities1). For Enjoyment: King Lear by William Shakespeare (16Personalities1) For Growth: Tribes: We Need You to Lead Us by Seth Godin (16Personalities1) 2024 Trending Picks for ENTJs: According to Charlotte Dune3, ENTJs gravitate toward: The 48 Laws of Power How to Win Friends and Influence People Start with Why Alternative Recommendation: The 33 Strategies of War by Robert Greene - ENTJs will love the sharp, clever tone of this non-fiction book. Their strategic minds will be stimulated by the abundance of material to draw from and the methods devised by warriors throughout history (Psychology Junkie4) Notable ENTJ Challenge: Charlotte Dune3 observes that ENTJs don't read many books because they're too busy being the BOSS and they don't like clutter. If they do read a book, it will be something they \"think\" they should read, but they'll think it's a waste of time and may not finish reading it because they have better things to do. ENFJ Reading Preferences and Recommendations Core Reading Philosophy: Protagonists (ENFJs) have a heart for the people they inspire. They may benefit from books with the same vibe (16Personalities1). ENFJs tend to read widely and have \"good\" taste and strong taste in books. They are the type to lead a public book club (Charlotte Dune3). For Enjoyment: The Secret Life of Bees by Sue Monk Kidd - The book is a nod to the power of forgiveness and the value of loving support and community (16Personalities1) For Growth: Authentic Happiness by Martin E. P. Seligman (16Personalities1) 2024 Trending Picks for ENFJs: Charlotte Dune's extensive ENFJ list3 includes: Desert Solitaire by Edward Abbey The Sex Lives of Cannibals: Adrift in the Equatorial Pacific by J. Maarten Troost The Life and Times of the Thunderbolt Kid by Bill Bryson Jitterbug Perfume by Tom Robbins The Sea Wolf by Jack London Endurance: Shackleton's Incredible Voyage by Alfred Lansing The Three-Body Problem Series by Cixin Liu Team of Rivals: The Political Genius of Abraham Lincoln by Doris Kearns Goodwin Illuminatus Trilogy by Robert Anton Wilson and Robert Shea Alternative Recommendation: I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings by Maya Angelou - ENFJs will find a kindred spirit in Angelou; this writer is considered by many to be an ENFJ herself. Her hope, vision, passion, and motivation to help others will be inspiring to like-minded ENFJs (Psychology Junkie4) Why These Books Work for Dynamic Leaders Dynamic Leaders seek books that combine practical leadership insights with deep understanding of human nature. They appreciate works that show how great leaders navigate complex challenges while maintaining their vision and values. ENTJs prefer strategic, results-oriented content, while ENFJs gravitate toward stories that illuminate the emotional and inspirational aspects of leadership. 4. The Innovative Explorers: Possibility-Focused Readers (ENTP, ENFP) Understanding the Explorer Mind Innovative Explorers are idea collectors who love books that challenge assumptions and offer multiple layers of meaning. They appreciate authors who aren't afraid to take creative risks and present fresh perspectives on familiar themes. ENTP Reading Preferences and Recommendations Core Reading Philosophy: Debaters (ENTPs) value gathering pockets of information, which they assemble into airtight arguments or compelling ideas. They get some pleasure out of defeating someone in an argument or turning people's heads with unique takes on different matters (16Personalities1). For Enjoyment: Hard-nosed detective novels such as the Easy Rawlins books by Walter Mosley, especially Devil in a Blue Dress - Publishers have published thousands of such novels from this genre about detectives who get the upper hand by cleverly unfolding mysteries and showing disdain for the bad guys (16Personalities1) For Growth: Freakonomics: A Rogue Economist Explores the Hidden Side of Everything by Steven D. Levitt and Stephen J. Dubner (16Personalities1) 2024 Trending Picks for ENTPs: Charlotte Dune3, identifying as an ENTP herself, shares her favorite books from 2024: The Singularity is Nearer When We Merge with AI by Ray Kurzweil Creation Lake by Rachel Kushner Blotter: The Untold Story of an Acid Medium by Erik Davis The Morning Star by Karl Ove Knausgard Scammer by Caroline Calloway Some Like it Darker by Stephen King Alternative Recommendation: Fight Club by Chuck Palahniuk - ENTPs will love the imaginative connections Chuck Palahniuk forms in Fight Club. Palahniuk himself is rumored to be an ENTP, and his ever-shifting honest perspectives and powerful insight into humanity and hidden agendas will keep the Ne-dominant mind entertained and inspired (Psychology Junkie4) ENTP Reading Philosophy: ENTPs like complex ideas, drama and chaos, spice and trying on different identities, chewing on problems, and feeling smart. They like to think about the future and endless possibilities, large ensemble casts, snark, and laughter. You can give an ENTP pretty much any book and they'll like it as they are loyal to no genre and want to experience the best of every genre (Charlotte Dune3). ENFP Reading Preferences and Recommendations Core Reading Philosophy: Campaigners (ENFPs) are often purpose-driven individuals, as long as the purpose also provides some excitement. They are true Extraverts with an appreciation for being social and seeking out the novel, but they are also emotionally vulnerable and can stress easily (16Personalities1). For Enjoyment: The Complete Collected Poems of Maya Angelou - From Angelou's earliest poems to her last, we get a glimpse into her world as she covers many of life's topics (16Personalities1) For Growth: Born a Crime by Trevor Noah - the famous comedian's account of growing up in apartheid South Africa as a biracial young person (16Personalities1) Alternative Recommendation: The Beach by Alex Garland - ENFPs will enjoy the many levels at which this novel operates. On one level it's a fast-paced adventure story; on another level, it explores why we search for utopias and refuges from the outside world. The novel asks harrowing questions about humanity and whether we are incapable of destroying the very sanctuary we seek (Psychology Junkie4) Why These Books Work for Innovative Explorers Innovative Explorers thrive on books that offer intellectual stimulation combined with creative storytelling. They appreciate works that challenge conventional thinking while providing multiple entry points for analysis and discussion. ENTPs particularly enjoy books that give them ammunition for debates and unique perspectives to share, while ENFPs gravitate toward works that combine adventure with deeper questions about human nature and social possibilities. 5. The Reliable Guardians: Tradition-Respecting Readers (ISTJ, ISFJ) Understanding the Guardian Mind Reliable Guardians appreciate books that reflect their values of duty, loyalty, and service to others. They enjoy well-crafted narratives with clear moral frameworks, historical depth, and characters who demonstrate integrity under pressure. ISTJ Reading Preferences and Recommendations Core Reading Philosophy: Logisticians (ISTJs) work hard and establish themselves as people who can be relied on. A sense of integrity is often what drives Logisticians (16Personalities1). According to Charlotte Dune3, ISTJs love novels with classic protagonists, strong heroes, historical significance, and deep social meaning. They are escapist readers because their lives are so practical and organized, and they love order and magic systems. For Enjoyment: The Bourne Identity or any of the Bourne books by Robert Ludlum - Jason Bourne: talk about a reclusive guy who gets things done (16Personalities1) For Growth: Quiet: The Power of Introverts in a World That Can't Stop Talking by Susan Cain (16Personalities1) 2024 Trending Picks for ISTJs: Charlotte Dune's research3 shows ISTJs currently enjoying: Trust by Hernan Diaz Normal People by Sally Rooney Classic sweeping sagas like Pride and Prejudice, The Hunger Games, and The Royals Historical works like Just Kids by Patti Smith and The Good Lord Bird by James McBride Investment and productivity books like The Intelligent Investor by Benjamin Graham and Black Swan by Nassim Taleb Alternative Recommendation: The Hunt for the Red October by Tom Clancy - ISTJs will appreciate the accuracy with which Clancy writes about submarine operations, the heroism of Jack Ryan, and the suspense that keeps the whole story moving at such a fast pace (Psychology Junkie4) ISFJ Reading Preferences and Recommendations Core Reading Philosophy: Defenders (ISFJs) are imaginative in practical ways and are diligent, paying attention to what others might call mundane details (16Personalities1). For Enjoyment: Any Agatha Christie novel, particularly Murder on the Orient Express - Defenders' detail-oriented powers of observation could easily mimic the perfect Agatha Christie detective. Miss Marple comes to mind (16Personalities1) For Growth: Chatter: The Voice in Our Head, Why It Matters, and How to Harness It by Ethan Kross - We Introverts spend a lot of time talking to ourselves in our heads. Learning to have a better relationship with that voice doesn't hurt (16Personalities1) Alternative Recommendation: Beneath a Scarlet Sky - ISFJs will enjoy the fact that the story is based on real events, and will relate to a hero who puts the needs of others far beyond his own (Psychology Junkie4) Why These Books Work for Reliable Guardians Reliable Guardians are drawn to books that combine compelling storytelling with clear moral foundations. They appreciate narratives where hard work, integrity, and dedication to duty ultimately triumph. ISTJs particularly enjoy systematic world-building and historical accuracy, while ISFJs gravitate toward character-driven stories that highlight selflessness and community support. 6. The Practical Organizers: Results-Oriented Readers (ESTJ, ESFJ) Understanding the Organizer Mind Practical Organizers read with clear purposes in mind—they want books that make them better at what they do and help them serve their communities more effectively. They appreciate concrete advice and stories that demonstrate effective leadership and teamwork. ESTJ Reading Preferences and Recommendations Core Reading Philosophy: Executives (ESTJs) are known for the way they value leadership through practical logic and order. They are often team leaders who expect others to be as dedicated and competent as they are (16Personalities1). Executives are the only personality type to choose technical/educational material as their favorite genre (16Personalities1). For Enjoyment: Lord of the Flies by William Golding - As the stranded boys in this novel try to organize themselves, they reveal how far off the rails unbridled human nature can take a group of people if they are not careful (16Personalities1) For Growth: Who Moved My Cheese? by Spencer Johnson, MD (16Personalities1) Alternative Recommendation: Make Your Bed by Admiral William H. McRaven - ESTJs will enjoy the no-nonsense, practical advice offered in this book and they'll get inspiring tips to become more influential leaders, parents, and friends (Psychology Junkie4) ESFJ Reading Preferences and Recommendations Core Reading Philosophy: The same loyalty and sense of duty that we see in other Sentinels are part of the typical Consul (ESFJ) makeup, but these personalities have a more expressive heart. Sometimes Consuls become enmeshed in other people's lives a bit too much (16Personalities1). Consuls are the only personality type to choose mystery/thrillers as their favorite genre (16Personalities1). For Enjoyment: The Lord of the Rings trilogy by J.R.R. Tolkien - Values and camaraderie abound during the quest that serves as the core of the story (16Personalities1) For Growth: Don't Sweat the Small Stuff…and It's All Small Stuff by Richard Carlson (16Personalities1) Alternative Recommendation: The Lost History of Stars - ESFJs will enjoy the hard-working, determined, and brave character of Lettie, and they will appreciate how she uses past experience to remain brave for her family and friends (Psychology Junkie4) Why These Books Work for Practical Organizers Practical Organizers appreciate books that combine entertainment with practical application. They want stories that demonstrate effective leadership principles and community building, along with non-fiction that provides actionable strategies for improving their effectiveness. ESTJs prefer systematic, results-oriented content, while ESFJs gravitate toward works that emphasize relationship building and community support. 7. The Independent Craftspeople: Skill-Focused Readers (ISTP, ISFP) Understanding the Craftsperson Mind Independent Craftspeople value books that celebrate individual skill, authenticity, and characters who forge their own paths. They're drawn to stories about practical competence and artistic expression. ISTP Reading Preferences and Recommendations Core Reading Philosophy: Virtuosos (ISTPs) are among the most practical types. They are masters at thinking on their feet and wizards at using tools. They tend to be among the most independent of personality types as well (16Personalities1). For Enjoyment: One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest by Ken Kesey (16Personalities1) For Growth: Shop Class as Soulcraft: An Inquiry into the Value of Work (also titled The Case for Working with Your Hands) by Matthew B. Crawford (16Personalities1) Alternative Recommendation: Black Hawk Down: A Story of Modern Warfare by Mark Bowden - ISTPs will be drawn to the courage, heroism, and determination of the soldiers in this epic true story (Psychology Junkie4) ISFP Reading Preferences and Recommendations Core Reading Philosophy: Adventurers (ISFPs) are charming, sensitive, and imaginative. They are drawn to the innovative or unusual. This likely determines the type of book that they might appreciate (16Personalities1). For Enjoyment: The Alchemist by Paulo Coelho - about the spiritual development of a shepherd boy as he journeys in search of treasure (16Personalities1) For Growth: Steal Like an Artist by Austin Kleon - A fun book about being creative (16Personalities1) Alternative Recommendation: The Language of Flowers by Vanessa Diffenbaugh - ISFPs will be drawn to the courage, independence, and ruthlessness of Victoria. They'll enjoy the complexity of her character, and the lush beauty and mystery of the flowers she surrounds herself with (Psychology Junkie4) Why These Books Work for Independent Craftspeople Independent Craftspeople appreciate books that celebrate individual competence and authentic self-expression. They're drawn to protagonists who demonstrate practical skills under pressure and who maintain their integrity despite external challenges. ISTPs prefer action-oriented narratives with technical accuracy, while ISFPs gravitate toward emotionally rich stories that explore themes of artistic expression and personal growth. 8. The Energetic Performers: Action-Oriented Readers (ESTP, ESFP) Understanding the Performer Mind Energetic Performers want books that match their energy level—they prefer stories that grab them immediately and maintain momentum throughout. They appreciate engaging characters and fast-paced narratives that keep them turning pages. ESTP Reading Preferences and Recommendations Core Reading Philosophy: Entrepreneurs (ESTPs) are bold and action-oriented. They are often practical and ambitious, but they may see it all as a game – a serious game, but a game (16Personalities1). However, Action-oriented Entrepreneurs are the personality type least likely to agree that time spent reading is important, with only 53% agreeing (16Personalities1). For Enjoyment: The Fountainhead by Ayn Rand (16Personalities1) For Growth: Getting Things Done: The Art of Stress-Free Productivity by David Allen (16Personalities1) Alternative Recommendation: Sherlock Holmes: The Ultimate Collection - Sir Arthur Conan Doyle, the author of the Sherlock Holmes mysteries, is an ESTP, so it's only natural that ESTPs would be drawn to his books! This collection contains 12 adventures and 11 memoirs. The adventures are short, concise, but full of mind-bending mystery and action. They will engage the ESTP's clever mind and keep up with their adventurous, action-oriented sensing side (Psychology Junkie4) ESFP Reading Preferences and Recommendations Core Reading Philosophy: Entertainers (ESFPs) are the consummate social butterflies. They love to hang around with fascinating people and offer such beguiling individuals unforgettable experiences in return. They are bons vivants who generally know what to do during any social situation (16Personalities1). For Enjoyment: The Crazy Rich Asians trilogy by Kevin Kwan - about the social antics of superrich Singaporean and Chinese families. A fun romp for"}]},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"[Content truncated — view full chat at source URL]"}]},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Source: "},{"type":"link","href":"https://www.genspark.ai/spark?id=1c40aa65-d745-4fca-98c7-1588177f8437&from=fork","children":[{"text":"https://www.genspark.ai/spark?id=1c40aa65-d745-4fca-98c7-1588177f8437&from=fork"}]}]}]
